# Implementation Plan

This is a simple 30/60/90 day rollout plan for implementing a digital referral and appointment management tool into an NHS outpatient service.

## Days 1-30: Discovery

The first month should be focused on understanding the current service before trying to change it.

Main actions:

* meet admin staff, clinicians, service manager and operational lead
* understand how referrals currently enter the service
* map the referral-to-appointment workflow
* identify existing systems, spreadsheets and manual workarounds
* understand where delays, errors or duplicated work happen
* agree baseline metrics
* identify a small pilot area
* identify possible super-users or early champions

Key questions:

* where does the biggest delay happen?
* which staff groups are most affected?
* what data is reliable?
* what information is missing from referrals?
* what workarounds are staff already using?
* what would make users resist the new tool?

## Days 31-60: Pilot

The second month should focus on a small pilot rather than a full rollout.

Main actions:

* start with one clinic or specialty area
* train admin users, clinicians and managers around their actual tasks
* set up a simple issue log
* run weekly feedback sessions
* monitor whether users are adopting the tool or reverting to old processes
* track early metrics such as referral-to-triage time, booking errors and DNA rate
* feed structured feedback back to the product or configuration team

What I would watch closely:

* are staff actually using the new workflow?
* are they duplicating work in the old system?
* are any steps slower than before?
* are patients being booked correctly?
* are clinicians getting enough information to triage safely?
* are managers getting useful visibility?

## Days 61-90: Wider rollout

The final month should focus on scaling only once the pilot is stable.

Main actions:

* expand to more clinics if the pilot is working
* update training based on pilot feedback
* create simple playbooks and FAQs
* review adoption and operational metrics with leadership
* agree BAU ownership after implementation
* continue tracking benefits and unresolved risks
* decide what needs product/configuration improvement

## Success metrics

* referral-to-triage time
* time from referral to appointment booking
* DNA / cancellation rate
* booking error rate
* clinic utilisation
* documentation completion time
* active usage by staff group
* number of manual workarounds still being used

## Main principle

Implementation should not be treated as complete at go-live. Go-live only means the tool is available. The real test is whether staff use it, trust it, and whether the workflow is measurably better than before.

